Other Opportunities: To Whom It May Concern,

My name is Catrina Brewton, and I am the African American Center Librarian at the San Francisco Public Library. I would love to speak with someone about ways that the library can help the Bayview Senior Services Senior Ex-Offender Program. A couple of ideas include teaching an introductory technology class (we have a lab here at the Main Library), hosting a film night, or providing a space for programs and support groups. I'm open to other ideas as well, as I appreciate the mission of the Senior Ex-Offender Program and would love to find ways the library can help and get involved.

Thank you for your time and hope to hear from you.

Other Opportunities: The California Council on Gerontology and Geriatrics is a non-profit statewide organization consisting of students, academicians, aging network service providers, businesses and advocates dedicated to enhancing the quality of life of California’s diverse aging population. Each year we convene a conference to inform members and associates of state-wide legislative policies, workforce development efforts, educational activities, and scientific research relevant to our mission of promoting the health and well-being of older adults and their families. A major goal of our annual meeting is to promote opportunities for networking and collaboration among students, faculty, service providers, businesses, and legislators.

We are excited to invite you to our 36th annual conference “Fostering Active and Purposeful Aging: A California Journey” in Sacramento on October 28, 2016. We hope you will join us as a conference exhibitor (https://memberplanet.com/s/ccgg/2016meeting_1) or attendee
(https://www.memberplanet.com/s/ccgg/2016meeting).

Please visit our 2016 Annual Meeting website (https://ccgg.org/annual-meeting/2016-annual-meeting/) to learn more about the conference, our meeting venue, and to register for the meeting. We encourage your participation as an exhibitor as that provides the most comprehensive opportunity for networking with our conference attendees. Exhibiting is an excellent way for organizations to disseminate information about their programs and services. The exhibiting fee covers the cost of one person to attend conference presentations when not at the exhibit table and includes lunch. We also welcome the participation of individuals of your organization as meeting attendees. The meeting day runs from 8:00 AM – 4:00 PM.

Unable to attend? Please consider a tax-deductible contribution to CCGG to support student scholarships and networking events, annual meeting symposia and panel presentations, awards for students, emerging and lifetime leaders, and age-friendly businesses in the community, or the James and Betty Birren Endowment.

We hope to see you in Sacramento in October!

IP Address: 134.139.170.13
Contact Form URL: https://bhpmss.org/volunteer/

Other Opportunities: Hello!
My name is Kelly and I am the lead counselor of the K-2nd grade cohort at Magic Zone, the after school program that functions out of the Ella Hill Hutch Community Center. We lead an 8-week long summer program and have included a Day of Give Back at the end of the summer to teach the youth the importance of giving back to their community. We were hoping to come into your space and have the kids read with or play games/spend time with the seniors on Friday, July 21st anytime between 10:00am and 3:00pm. We would have about 20 different 5-7 year olds and about 3 adults present to supervise. Please let me know as soon as you can if you think this is a possibility!

My name is Kelli Schultz and I'm the Office Manager for a company called Homebase here in the Bay Area. You guys use our software for your workers to clock in and clock out! We are looking for upcoming volunteer opportunities around the holidays for our 15-20 employees to do and we really want to serve one of our existing customers. Do you have anything we can help you with in the next few months? We have a group of about 15 incredible engineers/marketers. We can help behind the scenes or help serve meals? We want to give back to our customers in whatever way possible, especially the ones like you who are doing such incredible things for the community! Let me know how we can help!

item.content:encoded:
Hello,
We hope this letter finds you well. We are the Sunset Singers. We are a non-profit organization and we sing at senior centers, hospitals, restaurants, and other venues. We would love to come perform at Bayview Senior Services.
To tell you a little bit about ourselves, we are two middle school girls who love to sing and act. We have multiple theatre credits around the Bay Area and we created this organization because we believe that everyone deserves the chance to listen to music and enjoy themselves.
The great thing about our project is that our performances are free of charge because we believe there is no price on a good time. All we ask of you is your time and a listening ear.
If you are interested, please look below at a list of songs we are able to sing. Please chose some that you or the Seniors might enjoy and we will set up a date and a time for our performance.
Thank you!
Please let us know if you have any questions.
Best, Sunset Singers (Sydney Fish and Charlotte Kearns)
For Good - Wicked
House of the Rising Sun - The Animals
Here Comes the Sun - The Beatles
You Will Be Found - Dear Evan Hansen
The Girl I Mean to Be - The Secret Garden
Superboy and the Invisible Girl - Next to Normal
Hey Jude - The Beatles
Let it Be - The Beatles
I Wanna Dance with Somebody - Whitney Houston
Don’t Stop Believin’ - Journey
Send in the Clowns - A Little Night Music
Do-Re-Me - Sound of Music
Edelweiss - Sound of Music
My Favorite Things - Sound of Music
I Could’ve Danced All Night - My Fair Lady
Respect - Aretha Franklin
Sweet Caroline - Neil Diamond
Ain’t No Mountain High Enough - Marvin Gaye
Stop! In the Name of Love - The Supremes
You are the One that I Want - Grease

item.content:encoded:
Hello, I am the Program Manager with Employment Plus, a community based NPO in the city that works with adults with disabilities. We currently have two groups of 4 people that are looking for a new place to volunteer.
One of the groups is experienced in janitorial work and basic grounds maintenance. They are most comfortable with tasks such as cleaning and sanitizing bathrooms, collecting trash from multiple office trash cans, sorting trash/recycling/compost, vacuuming, and sweeping. I know often these tasks are the responsibility of office staff when there isn’t enough work for full time janitorial staff. This group would ideally volunteer for 1-2 hours 1 or 2 times a week.
The second group is also experienced with janitorial work but would like to focus more on working in the community and practicing customer service skills like interacting with a variety of different people while serving meals or possibly visiting seniors. The group would like to volunteer one day a week, preferably Monday afternoons.
Thanks for taking the time to read this message, and of course these are just suggestions of how these two groups may be able to volunteer but if there are other needs that BHPMSS has at any of your locations I am sure we would be able to assist. item.content:encoded:
Hello, I live at Turk and Divisidero and am interested in one, or both, of the following volunteer activities if available with the Western Addition Senior Center. I have been in SF for a year and a half now and was previously a volunteer with Nokomis Healthy Seniors in Minneapolis before moving here. Please let me know if there are opportunities available.
1. Visit homebound seniors: ideally this would be something that I could do with my small dog so I can incorporate exercise for her as well. I am also very willing to volunteer to walk small dogs for seniors on an average of once/week. This would serve as a longer walk than the dog might get on average (extra exercise). My dog would come on the walk as well.
2. I make handmade greeting cards and have led small group sessions with seniors in the past. I prepare all of the materials so the seniors can assemble cards and add decor. They take the cards with them for their own use. I provide the envelopes, but not postage. I can do this for a group of 6-8 seniors once every other month or once/quarter in the evening if a space can be provided.
Thank you! item.content:encoded:
Hi there,
I work for Dropbox and we are interested in a potential partnership with your organization. We would like to find out if you'd be interested in us offering our platform to your members free of charge. This would allow your members to have a safe, reliable way to store important documents and photographs in our cloud based storage platform. Ideally, we'd like to kick this off during Black History Month, but could be an ongoing effort. This project would be spearheaded by Black Dropboxers, our Employee Resource Group.
Please let me know if you'd be interested and who we should contact.
Thanks!

item.content:encoded:
Hello,
I work with SF based artist Sirron Norris, and our current project is with the SF Public Utilities Commission (SFPUC), which has a facility in the Bayview-Hunters Point. Our vision for this project is to offer cartooning classes to the Bayview community from various age groups in exchange for them completing a survey and having a discussion. The discussion and follow up survey would ask questions about what they would like to see in the Southeast Treatment Plan (STP) temporary fence. After each cartooning lesson, I will ask participants to complete a survey that would offer me additional insight.
The content of my survey will ask questions of past memories of STP, current issues, and gaping the interest of educating the community on what the STP actually does. Each student will be provided a sketch book made specifically for the project, along with pencils, and pens to use during and after the lesson. My goal is to engage at least 100 community members from various ages.
Please, if interested, let me know if you have availability in the early weeks of February to conduct 1-2 cartooning classes.
Thank you for your consideration. Kindly, Annabelle

I am 76 years old and would like to be of help if I can. I am computer savvy and would love to help elders navigate their technology. item.content:encoded: Hello, My name is Faaizah Arshad and I am an undergraduate student at UCLA. Community service has been a huge part of my life, and I have spent most of my time volunteering for senior centers and assisted living facilities. During the pandemic, I want to help provide assistance to caregivers and joy to senior citizens remotely. I really enjoy reading and spreading my love for reading, so I was wondering if I could coordinate a volunteer opportunity with the Bayview Senior Center in which I spend a couple hours each week reading books and short stories to senior citizens through an online platform like Zoom. I hope this message finds you well - I just wanted to see if we might be able to serve your community in the coming year. I am one of the managers at Social Call, an SF-based program that serves adults over 60 nationwide with long-term 1:1 friendly visiting phone matches. We've been around for 13 years, and experienced more than 100% growth over the pandemic - as you know, lots of volunteers & participants are looking for ways to live their lives to the fullest while simultaneously spending a lot of time inside their homes! I know during this time your programming has stayed creative & found lots of ways to pivot & serve everyone with these new contraints- it's quite a feat! I also wonder if the service we provide would be a fun thing to offer in addition to your existing portfolio of programming. I'd be happy to chat with you any time, and answer any questions you may have. item.title: About Us
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
For fifty years, Bayview Senior Services, (aka Bayview Hunters Point Multipurpose Senior Services) has responded to community needs and served as a catalyst for neighborhood activism and advocacy. Programs are designed to enhance and retain the health, quality of life, and culture of African American elders who remain as long standing members of communities in San Francisco. We believe that when older adults and people living with disabilities in African American communities are cared for with dignity, honor and respect, they will be able to age in place and maintain a strong and vibrant cultural presence in San Francisco. Our programs, which are open to all seniors and persons with disabilities, include three senior centers, nutritious meals, information/ referral, case management, adult day health care, money management, a senior ex-offender program and housing advocacy. For 36 years, Bayview Senior Services has operated the Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center at 1706 Yosemite Avenue. This center was named after the agency’s executive director of 30 years, who passed away in 2010. It was his vision — and now that of the community — to create a one-of-a-kind, state-of-the-art senior center co-located with senior housing to ensure a safe and vibrant future for the neighborhood’s aging population. In June 2016, the dream became a reality with the grand opening of the new Dr. George W. Davis Senior Residence and Senior Center. The 15,000-square-foot new senior center allows for expanded programs and services. It was designed to engage seniors and improve their economic circumstances, health, and well-being. The co-located Dr. George W. Davis Senior Residence provides 120 units of housing for low-income neighborhood seniors and people with disabilities.
The long-term vision for Bayview Senior Services includes the continuum of care through the coordination of housing, social services, health care, financial services, recreation facilities and economic ventures that will ensure seniors have the option to improve their quality of life.

item.title: Message from the Executive Director
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded: Imagine a community that embraces its elders – that provides housing, recreational opportunities, wellness programs and social supports. Imagine a community that respects the historical contributions of those who came before them, and celebrates their legacy. Imagine a community that understands seniors make an important contribution to friends, families and neighbors. Imagine all this coming to life as an Aging Campus that provides what is needed for seniors to age -- in place and with dignity — in their own community. This was the dream of my late husband, Dr. George W. Davis. A long standing community activist working for the good of the community, Dr. Davis took great care during his three decades of leadership to develop ongoing relationships with local, state and federal agencies; to forge profitable partnerships with private developers, leading corporations, and private foundations. His charisma and humble integrity helped win support for Bayview Senior Services and his community. While we all miss his presence, Dr. Davis’s legacy lives on through his vision of an Aging Campus. We have expanded our campus adding our first supportive housing and a new senior center named in his honor.120 units of affordable senior housing co-located with a 15,000 square foot state-of-the-art senior center opened in June 2016. Dr. Davis would be the first to say that he did not do any of this alone. We stand on the shoulders of many dedicated seniors and supporters – people who dedicated their time and energies to Bayview Senior Services over the past forty-plus years. It has been a labor of love and a testimony to the resilience of the Bayview Hunters Point community. We can now say his dream of creating an Aging Campus is alive and we continue to expand our services for seniors within their communities. The support of many people brought us to this moment in time. Your involvement and financial support will continue to carry us forward as we offer Dignity, Respect, and Honor to our seniors. Cathy Davis, MSW Executive Director

item.title: About Dr. George W. Davis
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded: From his childhood in the projects of Oakland and Richmond, Dr. George W. Davis learned the value of community.  He grew up in an era when neighbors looked out for each other and elders were given their rightful respect.  He has always maintained this strong sense of community in everything he does. A high school counselor once told him that his highest expectation would be to become a janitor.  Like the true Mac-ite he was, he used this “advice” as his inspiration to earn his PhD and become a leading African American gerontologist who was widely respected for his leadership and advocacy throughout the Bay Area. He was a community leader in the true sense of the spirit of community.  He had been in the trenches of community work for over 30 years.  Day in and day out he remained dedicated to making life better for the underserved, African American elders in San Francisco’s Bayview Hunters Point district. The neighborhood knew him as “Doc”, and “Doc” was known everywhere from the neighborhood to City Hall.  He had been the Executive Director of Bayview Hunters Point Multipurpose Senior Services for the past thirty-two years, during which time he concentrated his fight for the entire community, creating programs for the seniors. Innovation and creativity were his hallmarks.  For the past thirty years, Bayview Hunters Point has celebrated Black Cuisine, an event that attracts hundreds of people from all over the Bay Area to celebrate the cultural heritage of soul food.  This celebration brings people of all races and incomes together and is the only event of its kind that celebrates the neighborhood’s cultural strengths. Dr. Davis always integrated his intellectual skill with practical solutions that benefit people.  His master’s thesis was written on senior inmates in prison and in 1999 he initiated the first senior ex-offender program in the United States.  This program has made a difference in the lives of the seniors themselves; as well as pointed out the need to reach out to ex-offenders as they re-enter the community as seniors. As a leader, Dr. Davis remained an advocate, true to the cause.  He had been working on a comprehensive, innovative plan for seniors in the neighborhood known as the “Aging Campus”, for the past ten years.  The first of its kind in the United States, the Aging Campus will provide housing and services throughout the neighborhood.  This dream is about to become reality, as Dr. Davis united the community to create something positive, with a lasting impact. Dr. Davis received numerous awards and recognition for his 32 years of service, including awards from Senator Feinstein, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, Senator Mark Leno, Supervisor Sophie Maxwell, the National Council of  Negro Women, just to name a few.  He is the founder of the National Black Aging Network.  He had been active in the field of gerontology, including serving as an associate faculty member at Stanford’s Geriatric Education center. Humbled by any recognition and accolades, he kept his focus on the causes of his people.  His gentle, yet vital advocacy for seniors included creating programs and services for their benefit, improving their health, enabling them to live independently, and remaining active in their communities.  He did this by bringing together individuals, organizations, businesses and the government agencies who serve them.  The best expression of his leadership was the fact that when people wanted to see something get done in Bayview Hunters Point, they came to see him. Ordained as a minister in 2000, Rev. Dr. Davis found joy serving as Associate Pastor of the Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church in San Francisco.  Dr. Davis endured many health challenges, including diabetes, being legally blind and three cancers. He always lived by the scripture “you walk by faith, not by sight”. He took on his health challenges as a test of his faith and showed others how to be courageous and strong. Recognizing, connecting and celebrating family was of the upmost importance to Dr. Davis.  He loved his family and was a great role model and mentor to all of them.   He leaves a legacy in his wife Catherine Davis; brother Wesley Davis and Gloria; children Lola Gerine Allen, William George Davis, II and Micki; Tonya Davis, Kristy Davis, Matthew Davis, Teri Jordan; brothers-in-law Carl and Robert Koechlin; Grandchildren:  Cassadine Davis, Jalani Davis, Jalen Davis, Jaliyah Davis, Marcus Davis; Jordan Green and Jonique Green; Nieces and Nephews Katrina Mix, Diana Evans and husband Virgil Evans, Cornelius Boney and wife Noretta, Renee Broom, Keith Dowdell, Rochelle Salary and husband Warren; Arlanda Graves; and a host of grandnieces and grandnephews; as well as Bayview Senior Services staff; the Metropolitan Church family and the Bayview Hunter’s Point community.

item.title: Black Cuisine
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
The Bay Area’s biggest lip-smacking, finger-lickin’ soul food celebration, will take place on Saturday, March 7th, from 11:00 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. at the 40th Annual Black Cuisine Festival in San Francisco’s Bayview Hunters Point, located at the Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center on 1753 Carroll Avenue @ 3rd Street Station. 

The free event, presented by Bayview Senior Services, will feature live music, vendor booths, a Kid’s zone, and a dazzling variety of food venues. Some of the offerings include fried chicken, catfish, oxtails, ribs, links, black-eyed peas, red beans and rice, greens, yams, mac & cheese, cornbread, sweet potato pie, peach cobbler, pound cake and other soulful delights--all of which will be sure to rival mama and grandmas’ down-home cooking.

Black Cuisine will also give soul food novices and chefs an opportunity to share their culinary talents by entering the Soul Food Cooking contest with winners receiving cash prizes. Last year’s festival drew more than 2,000 attendees and we anticipate that number increasing this year.

Individuals interested in volunteering at the event or entering the cooking contest can call (415) 822.1444 or email info@bhpmss.org for more information.

History of Black Cuisine 
Black Cuisine, the longest standing community festival in Bayview Hunters Point, attracts people from across the Bay Area to come together and celebrate African American culture. It started as a food tasting contest but has now become a well-rounded event with food booths, vendors, live entertainment, fun for kids, cookbooks, and the ever-popular cooking contest. The Black Cuisine Festival was created by our late executive director, Dr. George W. Davis, who wanted to highlight the positive cultural contributions of our elders. For the community there is a spirit of pride to show off the positive aspects of Bayview Hunters Point. The event has grown in its influence, attracting more than 2,000 attendees annually. The streets in front of the Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center are closed for the day of the festival and are filled with joy and fun. Black Cuisine is a chance to experience soul food at its best and celebrate the strong sense of community present in the Bayview.

 

Grab your food tickets --> https://www.eventbrite.com/e/40th-annual-black-cuisine-fest…

item.title: Black Cuisine 2022
item.dc:creator: lassiterd
item.content:encoded:
THANK YOU

We thank you for supporting our seniors and making Black Cuisine 2022 Successful Yet Again!

Soul food was born out of struggle and survival within the African American community.  

Although the African American community is one of the hardest hit during this pandemic, enduring almost every challenge and loss imaginable, we have continued to overcome time and time again.

Bayview Senior Services remains a pillar in the community that consistently provides nourishment for our communities' body and soul. Black Cuisine is deeply rooted in coming together to tell the stories of triumph from generation to generation by celebrating African American culture and heritage.

Your participation in Black Cuisine makes an important contribution to our work with Seniors. 

Thank You!

 

42 years of Black Cuisine: Food is Love. Black Cuisine is a delicious fundraiser for Bayview Senior Services.   It was founded by the late DR. GEORGE W. DAVIS  in 1979, highlighting the best of soul food and African American culture. What started out as a soul food cooking contest amongst seniors to educate youth about their rich African American history,  evolved into the longest standing festival in Bayview Hunters Point. The festival attracts thousands  with its food booths, vendors, live entertainment and other activities.

Black Cuisine 2020 was cancelled at the recommendation from San Francisco’s Department of Public health to cancel large non-essential events due to COVID-19. While the in person gathering was called off, meals were offered on a take out basis - thus the spirit of Black Cuisine prevailed.

Black Cuisine 2020 Media feature - https://www.ktvu.com/video/662323

item.title: Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
Creating new opportunities to create, learn, and contribute to the community
Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center serves as a hub of community services for our seniors and persons with disabilities.  It is the go to place for seniors in the Bayview Hunters Point community to connect with each other and find services featuring:
  • Nutritious noon meals
  • Brown Bag Wednesdays
  • Always Active Exercise Classes
  • Arts and Crafts
  • Computer Lab and Classes
  • Pool and Dominoes
  • Thursday Night - Whist and Dominoes
  • Cooking Demonstrations
  • Monday Night Jazz (seasonal)
  • Parties and Events
In addition to the services and structured programs, the Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center also serves as central meeting place — a true community center where some seniors can relax, catch up with their friends and neighbors, play pool or dominoes, and drink coffee. The Center retains the values of a community village that elders from historical Southern Black communities have brought to the Bayview, creating their own small town with people who have known each other for decades. Every Thursday, whist and domino night, pool tournaments, special events and the ever popular Monday Night Jazz Series makes the Senior Center a happening place. Call us at 415-822-1444. Open: Monday - Saturday: 9 am - 5 pm James Evans Coordinator for Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center 1753 Carroll Avenue (@3rd Street) San Francisco, CA 94124 (415) 822-1444

item.title: Adult Day Health Center
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
Reassurance for caregivers to have a safe place for their loved ones, empowering participants to engage in their healthcare and lifting up the spirits of those who are isolated and homebound

Bayview Hunters Point Adult Day Health serves as an extension of care, love, and support to families caring for their loved ones at home.It lifts up the spirits of those who would otherwise be isolated and homebound and it empowers elders and adults living with disabilities and chronic illnesses to stay engaged and remain active members in their community.

Adult Day Health provides:

  • Personal Care Assistance
  • Registered Nurse Assistance
  • Social Work Services
  • Physical Therapy
  • Occupational Therapy
  • Speech Therapy
  • Recreational Activities
  • Nutritious Meals and Nutrition Counseling
  • Psychological Counseling
  • Paratransit Transportation
The Program includes:
  • Dance Parties
  • Dance Competitions
  • Wii Sport Game Competitions
  • Wii Fit Exercise
  • Peer, Family and Caregivers' Support Groups
  • Arts and Crafts
  • Musical Entertainment
  • Movie Days
  • Birthday and Holiday Celebrations

Helping to navigate the complicated systems of social services and health care for seniors and persons living with disabilities

Information/ Referral

Searching for the resources and making the links that allow seniors and persons with disabilities to get the help that they need. Contact Christie at 415-647-5353 or email christie.folau@bhpmss.org.

Case Management

Help with navigating the complicated systems of social services and health care so that people can age in place. Contact Malorie Branch at malorie.branch@bhpmss.org.

Network For Elders

The Network for Elders is a senior empowerment organization designed to inform seniors about the issues and services that are important to them and their community. Monthly meetings are held at the Southeast Community Facility. If you’d like to get involved, please contact Mrs. Beverly Taylor at 415-822-8566

Money Management

Bill Payer and Representative Payee Services are offered to seniors in need of assistance with managing their finances, with the help of AARP volunteers. Contact Lawrence Boyd at 415-647-5353 or email Lawrence.boyd@bhpmss.org.

Housing Assistance

Sharing housing resources that people need to advocate for themselves and advocate for those who are most vulnerable. Contact Janet Brown at janet.brown@bhpmss.org.

Translation/Social Services

item.title: Money Management
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
Money Management Resources are available to provide:
  • BHPMSS helps seniors with bill payments, budgeting and representative-payee assistance.
  • It's a great opportunity to give to someone a little help and make a big difference.
  • Volunteers are able to help seniors pay bills and manage their expenses, so they can remain in the community.
  • Getting control of the finances is often the key to keeping an elder at home.
  • Seniors who become unable to manage their own funds are at risk for abuse and neglect.
  • Family members are not always in a position to help or can sometimes be the financial abusers themselves.
  • Money management can make a huge difference in the quality of life of a person who is vulnerable.
Contact Lawrence Boyd, Program Coordinator at 415-647-5353 for assistance.  Bayview Senior Connections located at 1753 Carroll Ave @ 3rd Street.

item.title: Senior Ex-Offender Program
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
Erasing the stigma of formerly incarcerated individuals and offering them a chance to give back to the community.
Our Senior Ex-Offender Program (SEOP) is the first ex-offender program in the United States to focus on seniors. The program reaches out to people 50 years and older who have been incarcerated or are about to be released from prison. Through counseling, referrals and social support, the program gives ex-offenders an opportunity for a new start. Program has comprehensive wrap-around services for senior ex-offenders; counseling before and after release, transitional support groups for men and women, health care counseling, certified addiction specialist to help with recovery issues, mental health services, clothing and hygiene products. The people served by this program have great needs in all areas, and their characteristics are different from those of seniors served through  the Senior Center and Adult Day Health Center. Many are much younger as the conditions of incarceration age people very quickly. Many are originally from the Bayview, but are homeless upon release. Drug addiction, alcoholism, AIDS, untreated diabetes, hypertension and cardiovascular disease, depression and unemployment are common. So is the desire to change their lives. The Senior Ex-Offender Program (SEOP) is committed to restoring self-respect through social modeling, providing care, guidance and services, and finding solutions to the challenges faced by ex-offenders. The SEOP provides case management to ensure that participants are receiving healthcare that will establish good physical and mental condition.  Through a contract with the S.F. Sheriff's Department, SEOP staff connect ex-offenders to services and community. The goal of SEOP, to help ex-offenders re-engage in the community, would not be met without first finding housing.  Therefore BHPMSS provides two transitional homes that give ex-offenders a chance to live in the community with support systems. Through this housing residents are able to find more permanent solutions that will keep them out of jail and contributing to their community. SENIOR EX-OFFENDER PROGRAM (SEOP) Mike Pasley, Director of SEOP mike.pasley@bhpmss.org 5600 A Third Street (@Armstrong) San Francisco, CA 94124 415-830-8042 ext. 1103

Research indicates that volunteers enjoy better health, make new friendships, stay active and involved in the community, and learn new skills. Make a difference: Be part of a national movement to transform America through the involvement of its citizens.  So much more can happen for those in need if we all are willing to give of ourselves. item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded: Just two blocks away from the Western Addition Senior Center is the site of Rosa Parks Senior Residence and the Rosa Parks Senior Center. The center serves the seniors in building, as well as the community at large. The center is open five days a week with some special programs on weekends. In October 2012, BHPMSS was able to expand services in the Western Addition at the newly renovated Rosa Parks Senior Center. Through a partnership with the S.F. Housing Authority and the S.F. Department of Aging and Adult Services, this center compliments the services offered at Western Addition Senior Center. Dorneshia Landers, Rosa Parks Senior Center Director, is working to bring more services and programs to this new site. BHPMSS is committed to bringing high quality meal services and programming to the seniors in Western Addition. Rosa Parks Senior Center 1111 Buchannan (at Golden Gate) San Francisco, CA 94115. item.title: Certificate of Preference
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
In the 1960s and ‘70s, Certificates of Preference were issued to many residents in Hunters Point and Western Addition when they were moved out of their homes by the San Francisco Redevelopment Agency when it was implementing the federally-funded urban renewal program. Many people, however, are unaware of the Certificate of Preference Program and may not know they are still eligible if they lived in households that were on Redevelopment property at that time.
A Certificate of Preference could be your ticket to newly developed properties in San Francisco. The Certificate of Preference gives the holder priority consideration on the waiting list to obtain a housing unit.
If you think you have a Certificate of Preference, call Bayview Senior Connections at 415-647-5353 and we will support you in understanding how to obtain your certificate.

item.title: Senior Centers
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded: Organizations like ours are essential to the quality of life in any community. We are deeply engaged with the community’s seniors, and care for them with the dignity, respect and honor they deserve. The agency – which provides safe and welcoming places where seniors find care, companionship, and essential support service – is a lively community focal point, providing elders with nutrition programs, health screenings, rehabilitation services, money management advice, networking opportunities and adult day health care -- as well as our nationally recognized senior ex-offender program.

item.title: Naming Opportunities
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded: Since 1971, Bayview Senior Services has operated the Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center. This center is named after the agency’s executive director of 30 years, who passed away in 2010. It was his vision — and now that of the community — to create a one-of-a-kind, state-of-the-art senior center co-located with senior housing to ensure a safe and vibrant future for the neighborhood’s aging population. This dream is now a reality. The new Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center is located in a new neighborhood housing complex at 1751 Carroll Ave at Third Street. This facility provides 121 units of senior housing, as well as our brand new 15,000-square-foot senior center with a full range of innovative support services. YOU can make an impact and be a part of this legacy by investing in a naming opportunity. Choose one or more naming opportunity that works best for you, your family, church, foundation or business. Remembrance stones, Andrinka symbols, and leaves on our donor tree. Download Pledge Information

item.title: InterGenerational Blog
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
William Rhodes

Curriculum 2020/21

Christmas 2021

InterGenerational Greeting Card

Seniors from Dr. Gerge W. Davis and students from Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Academic Middle school spend months together on zoom classes. They began to create strong interGenerational bonds. During several classes seniors and students shared their feelings about being isolated during the covid pandemic. The students at MLK wanted to find purpose and support for the seniors during this traumatic time. Therefore, the students decided to create a series of greeting cards for seniors who were shut in and could not see their loved ones.

InterGenerational Dance Exchange Project

For the past few months, I have been working in collaboration with the Yerba Buena Center for the Arts and Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Academic Middle School on a project entitled the Intergenerational Dance Exchange. Project participants included seniors from Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center and students from Martin Luther King, Jr. Academic Middle School. Seniors and students were initially videotaped sharing their best dance moves and then participated in a series of months-long virtual classes. The project concluded with a final compilation dance video, which premiered at the San Francisco Urban Film Fest, and the creation of wearable art items produced during the weekly virtual classes.
The students from Martin Luther King, Jr. Academic Middle School were so inspired by the seniors' classic dance moves that they developed a series of questions for the seniors. In each class, seniors and students shared their artistic creations and discussed comparisons between contemporary and historic dance. The Intergenerational Dance Exchange Project not only forged cross-generational connections, but also allowed participants to use the mediums of dance and art to express themselves and their connection to culture and community. 
This project would not have been possible without the support of Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center, Rebeka Rodriguez from YBCA and Marrissa Bergmann and Sarah Fe Harris from the Martin Luther King, Jr. Academic Middle School. I thank all my wonderful collaborators in creating a meaningful experience and bright spot in a difficult time.

InterGenerational Glass Making classes

InterGenerational Drumming class

InterGenerational Sip and Paint

InterGenerational Sip and Paints are fun paint classes which allows seniors and youth to create art together. The classes are taught by artist William Rhodes and the music is provided by James Evans. One Sip and Paint class was taught by artist Courageous Cunningham.After the covid pandemic classes were switched to zoom. Zoom classes ranged from 70 - 25 participants. Don Bowden does the video and  technical zoom support. 

Bayview Senior Services has a long history of informal intergenerational participation in its programming and had long wanted to create more structured activities that bring people of different generations together. Since 2019 I have been privileged to formalize an intentional InterGenerational Program with an art focus that brings together the Baby Boomer Generation with Gen Z, the newest Generation born between 1995-2015. The project embraces our ancestral oral tradition for our youth while combating social isolation that is deadly to our elders.

We are currently living through unprecedented times. While our world has advanced technologically, we are experiencing a rise in social isolation amplified by the Coronavirus pandemic. Along with the world, I am exploring new ways to foster interpersonal connections while adhering to shelter-in-place orders.
This new challenge has given birth to projects which utilize technology in support of ancient oral traditions. In this space, I’ll be sharing an example of how Bayview Senior Services’ InterGenerational Program is meeting the challenge.
  
Summoning the power of storytelling, we have engaged some of our seniors to share their experience with students from Meadows Livingstone school via telephone. Through these conversations, built upon questions and answers developed with the school’s staff, seniors shared their personal history. Each question and answer allowed the student and senior to explore forging a connection between the past, present, and future. Both students and seniors are encouraged to create artwork inspired by this project.  
To get involved with the InterGenerational program, please contact William Rhodes, Program Coordinator:
william.rhodes@bhpmss.org 1753 Carroll Ave., San Francisco, CA 94124


Meet some of the Interviewers

Meet Some of the Interviewees

Interview with Diane Bennett
By Sol Bowden

SB: Can you tell me your name?
DB: Diane Bennett

SB: Do you know why your family gave you this name?
DB: Bennett is my married name.  I took his name when I got married.  My family name is Walker.

SB: Can you tell me where you were born? (If not San Francisco when did you move here?)
DB: San Francisco, CA. At San Francisco General Hospital

SB: What year were you born?
DB: 1950

SB: Did your family tell you anything about the day you were born?
DB: Not really. My mother didn’t speak a lot about that.  It’s just June 25th, not any special holiday.  

SB: How large was your family?
DB: My mom had 6 children, 4 girls and 2 boys.

SB: What was it like living in your house with all those people? 
DB: There was a lot of women in our family.  So, we looked up to women.  Being part Indian descent, we kept close, in a circle, because the men were out at work.

SB: What was your favorite movie or book when you were young?
DB: The Christmas Carol

 SB: What do you want your children and grandchildren (if you have them) to remember about you?
 DB: I do have children, and grandchildren and I have great grandchildren.  I have an art ability around making jewelry and color coordination.  I would like to share that whatever you do, including going to college, cultivate the arts or a particular skill so that you may have something to fall back on.

SB: How are you doing today? 
DB: I’m good. I’m making masks for the seniors. The one for your face.  One of the ladies for the senior center helped with it by getting the fabric.

SB: Do you have a sewing machine or do it by hand?
DB: I’m using a sewing machine. Both my grandmothers, mom, and aunts all knew how to sew.

SB: What life advice would you like to share with young people?
DB: To stay together, each one teaches one.  If you have a talent that your friend doesn’t have , teach them.

SB: I would like to meet your class.  Thank you for  this interview. 
DB: You’re welcome.  Thank you for being present.

Interview with Ms. Sheron Romes
By Malia Morales

MM: Do you know why your family gave you your name?
SR: My parents named me after a flower.

MM: Can you tell me where you were born?
SR: I was born in Chicago, IL, and moved to the Bay Area July 5, 1965.

MM: When’s your birthday?
SR: I was born on June 26, 1955.

MM: How large is your family?
SR: I have 4 bothers, and 2 sisters.

MM: Are you the oldest?
SR: I am the third oldest of seven children.

MM: What was it like to have a lot of siblings?
SR: We were always laughing and having a good time. We enjoyed having their siblings around to play with.

MM: What was your favorite movie or book growing up?
SR: My favorite movie is the Sister Act. We both enjoy Whoopie Goldberg movies.

MM: What were the most memorable events to you when you were growing up?
SR: My most memorable events were spending time with family and playing in the snow back in Chicago. Every summer, my whole family would go to my auntie’s farm and pick apples. We also enjoyed watching our parents kill and pluck the chickens.

MM: Do you have fun picking and harvesting?
SR: Yeah, we had a fun time because my mom had seven kids and my aunt had eight, so there were seventeen children running around.

MM: What did you do for fun when you were a teenager?
SR: I was a nerdy teen. During high school, I joined BSU (Black Student Union), drill team, and continued to attend church every Sunday.    

MM: What time did you have to be home at night?
SR: I always had to be home before dark.

MM: Did you ever get in trouble?
SR: Yes. My brother’s girlfriend bribed my with three scoops of ice cream to participate in pranking her mother. The girlfriend lied and said that I had been injured and had been taken to the county hospital for treatment. While walking home with my ice cream, I saw my mom and the community preparing to see me in the hospital, so I ran over and left my ice cream to splat on the sidewalk. I was later punished for participating in the lie.

MM: How did you like to dress?
SR: My mother handmade our clothing, so we dressed cool in original outfits.
MM: What was the fashion back then? And did you ever wear them?
SR: The fashion was hot pants and short skirts but I never wore them.

MM: What were the dances back when you were growing up?
SR:  The dances were the mashed potatoes and the twist.

MM: What was your first job?
SR: My first job was babysitting in San Mateo.

MM: What was your favorite job?
SR: My favorite job was being a cashier at a retail store. Now, it’s helping the elderly.

MM: Do you have any kids and grandkids?
SR: I have four daughters, who gave m two granddaughters and two grandsons. I currently live with one of my granddaughters.

Interview with Ms. Jean Wilson
By Axel Palms

I had a conversation with Miss Jean Wilson. “I'm blessed,” she says. “I have emphysema. Thanks to God I'm still here. I’m Miss Jean Wilson. Call me by my first name, Miss Jean. I'm from Texas. You have to call people by Mrs. or Mr.” Miss Jean only has one sibling, her sister Pamela. Pamela is a flight attendant for Delta Airlines. Miss Jean was the only child for 20 years until her sister was born. Miss Jean has first cousins with whom she is very close. They went to the store, movies and they loved each other so dearly. She said we need to get that love back. People need to be kind to each other. “People used to tease me because I was very tall. Children can be so mean to each other. I am a Christian. God made us all to love, love each other, strive for the best, and always hold your head high.” Miss Jean was born in Texas. She moved out to California. Her favorite movie was Imitation of Life, the original version. When she was little she always wished she could have a monkey. She told me to “be kind, be careful, be sweet, be safe.”

Interview with Ms Juanita Jackson
By Isis Shavers

IS: Can you tell me your name?
JJ: Ms Juanita Jackson.

IS: What year were you born?
JJ: 1953

IS: How large was your family?
JJ: 5 girls 1 boy.

IS: What was your favorite book or movie when you were young?
JJ: She didn’t really have one because she liked a lot.

IS: What was your favorite job?
JJ: Home care provider.

IS: What was your first job?
JJ: File Clerk.

IS: Do you have any children or grandchildren?
JJ: Yes I have grandchildren and children.

IS: What life advice would you like to share with young people?
JJ: Never give up.

Interview with Mr. Ira Watkins
By D’Andrew Shupert-Nadig

DS: Can you tell me your name?
Ira Watkins
At first I thought my family just picked the name out of the air but I think it was was a relative’s name.

DS: What year were you born?
1938. I was born in Waco, Texas.

DS: When did you move to San Francisco?
He moved to San Francisco around 1957. He came here for an adventure and because it was cheaper to live here.

DS: Did your family tell you anything about the day you were born?
He came from a large family and things about the day he was born never came up.

DS: How large was your family?
I had a large family – 2 brothers and 5 sisters

DS: Were they older or younger?
3 were older – 2 boys and 1 girl

DS: Did you get along with them?
They all got along with each other. They were not a fighting sort of family. They had disagreements from time to time, but never any physical fighting. That is still true today.

DS: Who were your heroes or people you looked up to when you were young?
I looked looked up to my parents when I was young. I admired their strength. I admired other people as well who were strong and stood up for what was right.

DS: What did you do for fun when you became a teenager?
When I was young, I shined shoes for fun and also shot pool.

DS: What time did you have to be home at night?
I had to be home by 5pm.

DS: What was your first job?
I shined shoes when I was young. That was my first job. I also shot pool until I was 25 and  made a living shooting pool. Of course, it cost a lot less to live back then and you could get by shooting pool.

DS: Do you have any children and grandchildren?
I have 1 daughter who has 2 children. I also have 2 great grandchildren.

DS: What life advice would you like to share with young people?
I  encourage kids to get a good education. A good education will give a child more options when they get older.

Interview with Mr. Alonzo Walker
By Alana Morales

AM: Do you know why your family gave you your name?
AW: I was named after his father’s friend. My full name is Mr. Alonzo Menelik Walker. Menelik was an emperor of Ethiopia.

AM: Can you tell me where you were born?
AW: San Francisco, California, General hospital.

AM: When were you born?
AW: October 9, 1948. I will be turning 72 this year.

AM: Did your family tell you anything about the day you were born?
 AW: Only that my birth was premature.

AM: How big is your family?
AW: One brother, two sisters, and myself.

AM: What is your favorite book/movie?
AW: My favorite movie is Muhammad Ali and My favorite book is The Holy Quran.

AM: What did you do for fun as a teenager?
AW: I played sports like track and field and baseball.

AM: Where did you hang out?
AW: I lived in Bayview Hunters Point, so he hung out at the park, libraries, and at my Jr. High school (middle school).

AM: What time would you have to be home at night?
AW: When I was a kid, I had to be home before dark and as a teenager at 9 o’ clock.

AM: Did you ever get in trouble?
AW: Yes, due to peer pressure I ended up in jail.

AM: What were the slang phrases back then?
AW: “What’s up”, “what’s happening”, :going to the crib” (also known as going home).

AM: What were the outfits back then?
AW: We wore polo shirts, leather jackets, with afros and braids.

AM: What was your favorite job?
AW: Working in the post office.

AM: What did you do in the post office?
AW: Sorted, stamped, and loaded mail for delivery.

AM: Did you ever have any children or grandchildren?
AW: No children, I have nieces and nephews only.

AM: What kind of music do you like?
AW: Motown, Smokey Robinson, Supremes and The Temptation!

AM: What do you think about today’s music?
AW: I’m not a big fan of gangster rap. I don’t like how it speaks of “the negatives.” Life should be about “the positive”, of a better human being. Music should inspire you when you’re young.

AM: Who is your favorite president?
AW: Mr. Barak Obama, President Obama is inspiring and encouraging.

AM: What do you think about Michelle Obama?
AW: She is an excellent role model for ladies.

Interview with Mr. Dennis Billups
By Darrow Feldstein

On April 13, 2020, I called up Mr. Dennis Billups to interview him and talk with him about his life. I had never met Dennis nor knew anything about him. When I called, he promptly asked if I knew who he was or anything about his story. I said no and he told me, “you have no ground to stand on. Go and watch the movie “Crip Camp” and call me back.” I was able to ask a few basic questions before we ended the call though. Dennis was born in 1952, the year of the dragon, in San Francisco. He’s lived in SF his entire life. Most of his family is from Texas but they’re now all on the west coast. There are 4 in his immediate family though his sister passed in 2011. She was also blind. Both Dennis and his sister were premature at birth. When they were put in incubators, they received too much oxygen and it burnt his and his sister’s corneas making them blind. Dennis has practiced meditation since being a young child and has put a lot of work and study into spiritual and contemplative study. He is well versed in astrology and numerology among many other schools of thought.
 
Dennis talked a bit about his work in the disability justice movement and the passage of 504—something I had no knowledge of. The day after our call, I watched the new “Crip Camp” movie and there was Dennis Billups being interviewed! And there was footage of him from the seventies occupying the federal building in San Francisco for 26 days! I realized I was talking with someone who had some real experience with leadership and justice movements.
 
I called him back the next day and we had a lovely and lively conversation about leadership and inner work, about care for others and about belief in there being something better afoot. He’s really sharp and has such a quick mind. And with someone like Dennis, set interview questions can’t really work. The interviewer must flow with him wherever the energy presents itself. Below is a poem inspired by my time with Dennis which I hope gets to the heart of our conversation together.
 
Leading from the heart
 
Harken back to days
when equity was a budding word
when the call to action was heard and lifted up to the light.
This man, no sight, rises to meet
that which is awake inside of him
that which he sees awake in all.
A commitment to inclusion and care,
A discipline for inner work and joy.
What do leaders need today I ask?
What must we learn from the past?
“Open up and listen”, he says
“stay grounded and aware of the call”
“leave no one behind and look out for one another
Always”.
I witness his wisdom and feel more
than I understand
Keep a laugh on the tip of my tongue
Keep the vision for liberation at the forefront.
This will not be easy,
But
The tides are shifting
currently.
Give thanks for the wisdom keepers
Who generously share.
May I pass forward the messages
and always remain
a learner.

Interview with Dolores Cunningham
By Jennie Bennett

JB: Do you know why your family gave you your name?
DC: I guess my mother gave me that name because it was beautiful and she just liked it.

JB: How large is your family?
DC: There were 5 girls and I am the oldest.

JB: What was your favorite book growing up?
DC: My favorite book is Black Nigeria.

JB: Who were your heroes/sheroes or people you looked up to?
DC:  I really looked up to Dr. Martin Luther King JR and President John Fitzgerald Kennedy.

JB: Do you have children or grandchildren?
DC: Yes, I had 3 kids. Sadly, my son died.

JB: What do you want your children and grandchildren to remember about you?
DC: It is important for them to remember how kind I was to everybody. Also how I was able to feed everybody. You know a lot of people don’t have a chance to feed themselves or even their children. I’m so glad that I got that opportunity.

JB: As an older adult what was the most difficult and rewarding time in your life?
DC: Well, when my son died. That was the most difficult time of my life. The most rewarding time for me was when I got to provide for my kids and give them as much as they wanted or needed.

JB: What life advice would you like to share with the younger people of today?
DC: My advice is to be more supportive and kind to people.  

Interview with Mary Fleming
By Melodie Kauff

Do you know why your family gave you your name?: Answer is, I guess my mother gave me that name because it was beautiful and that she liked it.
How large was your family?: Answer is, There was 5 girls and Dolores was the oldest.
What was your favorite book growing up?: Answer is, Black Nigeria.
Who were your heroes/sheroes or people you looked up to?: Answer is, MLK and President Kennedy.
Do you have children or grandchildren?: Answer is, Yes, I have 3 kids my son died though.
What do you want your children and grandchildren to remember about you?: How kind I was to everybody. Also how I was able to feed everybody cause a lot of people don’t have a chance to feed themselves or there children. So I’m glad that I got that opportunity.
As an older adult what was the most difficult and rewarding time in your life?: Answer is, when my son died was the most difficult time. Most rewarding to me was when I got to  give my kids as much as they want or need.
What life advice would you like to share with the younger people of today?: Answer is, To be more supportive and kind to people.

Interview of Mary Fleming by Melodie Kauff

In the beginning of our conversation Mary shared with me that she has been keeping busy during the time of shelter in place, with her artwork and with calls to friends and family, keeping up on the news and also mindful (and reminding friends) that too much of the news is depressing and repetitive. And keeps her TV tuned mostly to the religious station to be with god. 

Name: Mary Fleming- Mary Lou in elementary and junior high, pretty much once I got into high school I dropped the Lou. When somebody hears somebody else say Lou when I didn't give you that name when I introduce myself to you I prefer you didn't say it. 

Born: San Francisco CA. SF General Hospital. Born and raised in SF, CA. 1947. I'll be 73 on October the 20th

Who did you look up to when you were younger? My aunt and uncle. My mother grew up under her, and I did too, she was like the head of the house so I looked up to her. She owned her own house and a beauty shop business. She did a lot of traveling, she did a lot of things for us, so I looked up to her. Bertha Hill Randolph. Nobody messed with her. Plus she carried a 45 with her, even thought she was married to Uncle Joe, she was the dominant one. 

Siblings: 4 brothers and one sister, 2 of them, my sister and one brother are still alive. Moved a year ago to Las Vegas, we keep up on the phone. 

Most difficult and most rewarding: having my daughter. Difficult coming out, beautiful once they're here. She was a good baby. Very good baby and she's a beautiful woman now. Her personality, her smile, she treats people right, she's like me. 

Grandchildren: I got one granddaughter, Alicia Butler, one great granddaughter, Sydney Chapman, 33 and 13. They live in the city they come by and do things for me, like maybe take out the garbage or if I want something they go to the store if I don't feel like going. So pretty much I have everything I need in the house or I FaceTime them if I feel like it so we see each other, or I see them at the bottom of the stairs. I have 18 stairs so I just look down "hello!" from 6 feet away. So yeah, I see them. I haven't seen the baby girl since, but I talk to her pretty much every other day on the phone. 

Every year since she's been born I make a calendar, so I got a calendar from when she was born all the way up to 13. To have, unless anything destroys it or anything. 

How old were you when you got married? I was 18. Started going with my husband when I was 16, got pregnant at 18, and we got married. 

Life advice for young people: Get into a good church and start going to church and learn about god. Because we know all the evil that’s out here so learn the other side, the good side of life. Concentrate on god, Jesus Christ and the Holy Spirit. I grew up in church and I got baptized when I think I was about either 8 or 9. With my two cousins and my brother, my oldest brother, 4 of us got baptized on the same day.

What do you want your children and grandchildren to remember: She was a sweet loving grandmother and grandmother. And she loved her God, Jesus and Holy Spirit. 

I'm a self-taught artist, just started drawing and got better and better. 2016 started trying to do something. It feels good huh? Especially when it looks like what you're trying to draw. I started off liking animals more than I got into drawing people and whatever. Pencil and then paint. And then lately I’ve been liking just black and white without the color, but I go into spells. But I do like color. Favorite colors are yellow and red and I think blue. 

(I like those colors, fiery and watery)

That’s a hard thing to do, water, to me. I try to practice more and more a little and then I stop. But since talking to you I may try to do that today. Blues, greens, and then that white wave? That's what I have a problem with, the wave part for some reason. I’ve been practicing on the ocean. Kind of hard to me but I think I might work on that today because I’m talking to you and I’m looking at a picture I took when I was down in Acapulco, it reminds me of Cabo San Lucas, that rock with a hole in it. One of the shots is kind of well-known in different magazines. 

(You’ve done some traveling)

Yeah that’s a thing I picked up from my aunt. She travelled a lot. I learned that from my aunt. Besides working, travel. See it and my daughter she used to work a lot, every time from a. teenager she didn't go to parties she would work before she would go to a party so she worked a lot and I was saying "yaaaay!" Yeah forget the party anyway. So she just worked, worked, worked overtime they could always count on her at her job and stuff. I used to tell her, you can’t just keep working you got to take a trip or whatever now. Now she’s taking vacations. A lot of places I haven’t been because I pretty much like to go down and get on the cruise and go, like, to St. Thomas and all down there. I love the cruise. She's traveling to other places though. She was supposed to go to Greece this year you know, but that was cancelled until next year. So maybe next year I may go with em!

3rd Street Youth Center & Clinic

Sophia Liang Interviewing Rebba Middleton

SL: Can you tell me your name?
RM: Rebba Middleton.

SL: Do you know why your family gave you this name?
RM: I got it from the Davis senior center.

SL: Can you tell me where you were born?
RM: San Francisco.

SL: What year were you born?
RM: 1958.

SL: Do you have any children and grandchildren? If so, how many?
RM: No.

SL: What was your first job? What was your favorite job?
RM: Executive Assistant at a city bank. Real Estate Sales Consultant

SL: Who is the person that influenced your life the most?
RM: My parents.

SL: Which new technology have you found to be most helpful in your life?
RM: Cellphone.

SL: What was your favorite thing to do for fun when you were younger?
RM: Talking on the phone and hanging out with friends.

SL: What world events had the most impact on your life?
RM: 2008 Recession.

SL: Did you go to university or college? How did you decide what you wanted to study?
RM: Yes. I studied what was more practical, which was business. I followed what I enjoyed. I also enjoyed English and History, but I chose business because it was more practical.

SL: What advice would you give to your younger self?
RM: Save money. Don’t spend so much.

SL: What things are most important to you now?
RM: Spending time with my family, enjoying myself, and saving up for retirement.

Clementine Loh Interviewing Ms. Vashann Jackson

CL: Hi, is this Ms. Vashann Jackson?
MS. VJ: Yes

CL: My name is Clementine Loh, I’m 16 years old and I go to Burton High School. I am assigned to interview you for an assignment.

CL: Can you tell me your name, age (if you don’t mind me asking), and how many kids you have?
MS. VJ: My name is Vashann Jackson, I’m 46 and I have one son that goes to the same school you went to.

CL: Where were you born and raised?
MS. VJ: San Francisco

CL: How are you doing today?
MS. VJ: “I’m doing great, thank you for asking, how are you?”

CL: I said I was good.

CL: What is your job?
MS. VJ: Business Instructor

CL: What is a challenge you have as a Business Instructor and how did you overcome that challenge?
MS. VJ: A challenge that Ms. Vashann Jackson was trying to get people to exercise and that business should be a part of their life. She overcame that challenge by using social media to grab an audience and uploading videos showing people how much weight she lost and how she changed her lifestyle.

CL: Were there any major accomplishments you made as a Business Instructor?
MS.VJ: “I created a Business Bootcamp all across the Bay Area!”

CL: How did your job make you a better person today?
MS. VJ: “It kept me up on my lifestyle and at the same time, I was able to help other people with theirs.”

CL: What is your favorite part about being a Business Instructor?
MS. VJ: “Engaging with the community.”

CL: What life advice would you like to share with the people who are younger than you?
MS. VJ: “To start early and engage in what you really want to be when you grow up and to start that mindset process of thinking about. Focus on your future and think big.”

CL: Do you have any questions for me?
MS. VJ: No

CL: “Okay, great! That will be it for today. Thank you for taking your time to call me back and do this interview. Have a great rest of your day Ms. Vashann Jackson!”

MS. VJ: “Alright thank you, bye bye.”

Mia Santiago Interviewing Sonya Black

Hello, My name is Mia Santiago.
MS: Can you tell me your name?
SB: Sonya Black

MS: Do you know why your family gave you this name?
SB: not sure// older sister named her

MS: Can you tell me where were you born? (If not San Francisco when did you move
here?)
SB: San Francisco, General Hospital

MS: What year were you born?
SB: 1960

MS: What is your favorite childhood memory?
SB: Going swimming at MLK Pool, Tik Tok (a place to eat back then) had the best
French Fries

MS: How large was your family?
SB: 14 (12 kids)

MS: Who were your heroes or people you looked up to when you were young? And
who are your heroes now?
SB:
- MLK, President Kennedy
- Herself, Obama and Michelle
- ( She looked up to MLK dream’s, Obama gave her many opportunities)

M.S: What was your favorite movie or book when you were young? And what is your
favorite movie and book now?
SB:
- Movie: James Bond movies, Coffy, The Mack , book: Daniel Steel books (love
stories)
- Movie: Black Panther, book: N/A, (reading titanic with granddaughter currently)

MS: What big world events were the most memorable to you while you were growing
up?
SB: When she got to sit on the bus anywhere when she was 5 ( paid attention to black
panthers, taught her to be proud of her race)

MS: What did you do for fun when you became a teenager? Where did you hang out?
What time did you have to be home at night? Did you ever get in trouble? What were
the slang phrases that were popular when you were a teenager? How did you like to
dress?
SB: See her boyfriend, movies, on Market for the movie theater (tradition to go watch
movies)
- Movies on Market, library on Cortland, garage parties
- 10 pm, had Independence
- Yeah, cutting school // caught at another school
- Black power handshake,
- Cool: sizzler, puma shoes, baby doll shoes (lace-up boots), knickerbockers, afro

MS: What was your first job? What was your favorite job?
SB: Summer job, child care center (12 years old)

Andrea Phillips Interviewing Sheron Romes

A.P: Hi, My name is Andrea Phillips
S.R: Hi, my name is Sheron Romes

A.P: Hi, Sheron. I am with the 3rd Street Youth Center & Clinic and I have a few
questions for you. What is your career?
S.R: I am a CAN, working with the elderly. I’ve been doing it for the last 25 years!

A.P: What programs were you involved in?
S.R: CNA program in Oakland

A.P: Was it a good experience?
S.R: Yes, it was a very good experience.

A.P: Have you always wanted to be a CNA?
S.R: I have always helped my family members and after working at the senior center. I
was set with my career.

A.P: Okay, that great!
S.R: I actually haven’t performed being a CNA lately because I had a stroke and
aneurysm

A.P: Are you okay? I am sorry that happened to you.
S.R: Yes, I am okay.

A.P: Thank you for your time and responses. Stay safe. God Bless!
item.excerpt:encoded:
With the funding support of the California Arts Council, Bayview Senior Services brought people together across generational, cultural, racial, and geographic lines to share life experiences and artistic expressions during the pandemic.
Our ‘Senior Heroes’ project involved seniors sharing their Black experience through their respective lives in the arts, education, faith, community service, and activism. Working with the lead artist and the instructors from the school partners, we collectively came up with a plan to have people engage, educate and share art across generations.

item.title: Art for Aid
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
Art for Aid is a project which allows me to share my art and give back to the community. I am offering several of my original artworks to be sold and 100 percent of the proceeds will go to supporting the InterGenerational program at Bayview Senior Services. Your purchase will help fund community activities which engage and bring together youth and seniors. It will also fund and support our food services and education programing. I have been creating art for most of my life. The artworks for sale spans 4 decades and every piece reflects my changing styles and themes throughout the  years.

William Rhodes
I was born in Baltimore, MD and attended the Baltimore School for the Arts. I later received a BA in Furniture Building and Design from the University of the Arts in Philadelphia and a MFA from the University of Massachusetts at Dartmouth. My creative works are in the collections of various galleries and museums. Most recently, my work was included in the permanent collection of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture. Along with my studio art practice; I dedicate part of my time developing Intergenerational community based art projects and hosting art classes and tours throughout Italy. I am the co-founder of a Black art collective in San Francisco called 3.9. The 3.9 Art Collective was formed in 2011 in response to the declining Black population in San Francisco.

To purchase any of the art below contact William Rhodes at: william.rhodes@bhpmss.org

item.title: Black Cuisine 2021
item.dc:creator: lassiterd
item.content:encoded:
THANK YOU

We thank you for supporting our seniors and making Black Cuisine 2021 Successful Yet Again!

Soul food was born out of struggle and survival within the African American community.  

Although the African American community is one of the hardest hit during this pandemic, enduring almost every challenge and loss imaginable, we have continued to overcome time and time again.

Bayview Senior Services remains a pillar in the community that consistently provides nourishment for our communities' body and soul. Black Cuisine is deeply rooted in coming together to tell the stories of triumph from generation to generation by celebrating African American culture and heritage.

Your participation in Black Cuisine makes an important contribution to our work with Seniors. 

Thank You!

 To learn more about Black Cuisine & 

Bayview Senior Services 

(and enjoy some great music) 

Check Out Our Video Here:

[youtube https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lqiklaPMXDU&w=560&h=315]

[googleapps domain="drive" dir="file/d/14UlhkIWAO-GVsJ_o8BpagdoH8opa8Rxk/preview" query="" width="640" height="480" /]

41 years of Black Cuisine: Food is Love. Black Cuisine is a delicious fundraiser for Bayview Senior Services.   It was founded by the late DR. GEORGE W. DAVIS  in 1979, highlighting the best of soul food and African American culture. What started out as a soul food cooking contest amongst seniors to educate youth about their rich African American history,  evolved into the longest standing festival in Bayview Hunters Point. The festival attracts thousands  with its food booths, vendors, live entertainment and other activities.

Black Cuisine 2020 was cancelled at the recommendation from San Francisco’s Department of Public health to cancel large non-essential events due to COVID-19. While the in person gathering was called off, meals were offered on a take out basis - thus the spirit of Black Cuisine prevailed.

Black Cuisine 2020 Media feature - https://www.ktvu.com/video/662323

Black Cuisine 2021 festival was held virtually (see video above!).

item.title: 50 YEARS STRONG
item.dc:creator: lassiterd
item.content:encoded:
We have reached a milestone!
 
 On July 7, 2021, and throughout 2021, Bayview Senior Services celebrates 50 years of service to the community! The agency has a strong history of innovation on behalf of our seniors. 
 
Our late Executive Director, Dr. George W. Davis, had a vision for seniors to age in place, and we are continuing his legacy through providing a truly remarkable array of programs and services that do just that. 
 
 Over the years, our agency has grown into a multiservice organization serving seniors, persons with disabilities, and the community at large, but we have never forgotten where we started. 
 
Our programming has a holistic wellness lens that supports our clients' physical and mental health, from engaging homeless seniors and persons with disabilities to expanding nutrition services with fresh and quality food. 
 
The role of our donors, supporters, community partners, staff, and volunteers in keeping seniors healthy, housed, active, and socially connected is indeed a cause for appreciation and celebration. 
 
While we've reached a milestone, we are determined to go even further!

item.title: What Does It Mean To Belong?
item.dc:creator: lassiterd
item.content:encoded:
Danny Glover

In an era of gentrification and rapid community change, what does it mean to belong – and to age in place?

San Francisco has been one of the fastest gentrifying cities across the U.S., impacting Black communities’ ability to grow old in the neighborhoods that they’ve long called home.

In conversation with Danny Glover and others, we shine a light on San Francisco’s Dr. George Davis Senior Center to explore what it takes to age with equity.

item.title: Where Generations Come Home
item.dc:creator: lassiterd
item.content:encoded:
Event: "Where Generations Come Home"

Date and Time: Friday, March 25th 4pm -6pm

Location: Dr. George W. Davis Senior Center ( Court Yard)

Attendance: Free event but you must RSVP to: william.rhodes@bhpmss.org no later than 3/18/22  ( We only have 40 guest spaces available). 

Requirements: You must show proof of vaccination to attend the event.

Project Partners: This project is a collaboration between. The Intergenerational Program at Bayview Senior Services, SF Urban Film Fest, Studios of Key West and the Bahama Village Music Program.

Details: There will be live music performance by Lorerrta Gooden who is a Dr. GWD resident. There will be several short films shown and refreshments will be served. The event will conclude with a panel discussion between artist William Rhodes and Kawana Staffney -Ashe who is the Executive Director of the Bahama Village Music Program in Key West, FL. Both panelists will talk and answer questions about how the arts and Intergenerational exchange can preserve a community suffering from gentrification and displacement. 

Thank you,

William
item.excerpt:encoded: Join us for: short films, live music performance and a panel discussion.

item.title: Adult Day Health Center
item.dc:creator: bhpmss
item.content:encoded:
Reassurance for caregivers to have a safe place for their loved ones, empowering participants to engage in their healthcare and lifting up the spirits of those who are isolated and homebound
Bayview Hunters Point Adult Day Health serves as an extension of care, love, and support to families caring for their loved ones at home.It lifts up the spirits of those who would otherwise be isolated and homebound and it empowers elders and adults living with disabilities and chronic illnesses to stay engaged and remain active members in their community.
Adult Day Health provides:
  • Personal Care Assistance
  • Registered Nurse Assistance
  • Social Work Services
  • Physical Therapy
  • Occupational Therapy
  • Speech Therapy
  • Recreational Activities
  • Nutritious Meals and Nutrition Counseling
  • Psychological Counseling
  • Paratransit Transportation
The Program includes:
  • Dance Parties
  • Dance Competitions
  • Wii Sport Game Competitions
  • Wii Fit Exercise
  • Peer, Family and Caregivers' Support Groups
  • Arts and Crafts
  • Musical Entertainment
  • Movie Days
  • Birthday and Holiday Celebrations
To become a member of our Adult Day Health Family, please contact :

Raenika Butler, Program Director raenika.butler@bhpmss.org 415-826-4774 1250 Lasalle Ave. San Francisco, CA 94124

BHPMSS' Adult Day Health Center is licensed by the Department of Health Services
